o Goa (GOI) start at $32 for one-way and $74 for round trip. Earn your airline miles on top of our rewards! $29 is currently the lowest price for a one-way Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport to Dabolim Airport flight. A return flight starts at $65. These fares ... Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. The cheapest round-trip flight from Mumbai to Goa starts at $66 from Thu, Apr 9 to Mon, Apr 13. The cheapest one-way flight starts at $27 and departs on Wed, ... Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. Q: What is today's cheapest fare from Mumbai to Goa ? A: You can get the best airfare of \u2713Rs. 4328 when flying from Mumbai to Goa. Q: ... Flights between Mumbai and Goa starting at $39. Choose between IndiGo Airlines, Air India Limited, or Air India Express to find the best price. Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. Book flight ticket for Mumbai to Goa flights with Air India, with Air fare starting at INR 2859. Apply AISAVER to save up to \u20b91000 on air tickets for BOM to ... Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. One-way Nonstop flights from $27 \u2013 only 5 seats left for Mon, Mar 23 on IndiGo. Flash Sale! Nonstop round-trip flights from just $37 - IndiGo (Tue, Mar 10 - Tue ... Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. The cheapest flight ticket price from Mumbai to Goa on 22 Feb 2026 is \u20b92,109 by Air India, departing at 19:30. The earliest flight operated by Air India ... Missing: 2024 | Show results with:2024. What is the price range of a Mumbai to Goa flight? A. Mumbai to Goa Flight Prices usually vary between 71.93 - 71.93. Q. On which days one can have the most ... Goa.$35 per passenger.Departing Sat, Sep 19.One-way flight with Air India Express.Outbound direct flight with Air India Express departing from Mumbai on Sat, ..."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "**Today\u2019s lowest\u2011priced ticket from Mumbai (BOM) to Goa (GOI)**  \n\n- **\u20b9\u202f2,109** (\u2248\u202fUS\u202f$\u202f25) for a **one\u2011way** flight on **Air India**, departing **19:30 on\u202f22\u202fFeb\u202f2026** from Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport (BOM) to Dabolim Airport (GOI).\n\nThat figure is the most specific \u201ccheapest flight ticket price\u201d mentioned in the latest data you provided. If you book now you can lock in that fare (subject to seat availability)."}, {"role": "user", "name": "Travel_Researcher", "content": "Error occured in python script name [C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py] line number [13] error message [HolidayAgentException.__init__() missing 1 required positional argument: 'error_detail']"}], "response": {"id": "chatcmpl-df4e01e6-6089-4fc7-b13b-c23d5df76a49", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "stop", "index": 0, "logprobs": null, "message": {"content": "## What the error means  \n\n```\nHolidayAgentException.__init__() missing 1 required positional argument: 'error_detail'\n```\n\nThe traceback tells us that somewhere in **`GoogleMap.py`** (line\u202f13) you are **raising** (or instantiating) a custom exception called `HolidayAgentException`, but the constructor (`__init__`) of that class expects **two** arguments:\n\n```python\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n```\n\nWhen you call it you are only passing **one** argument (or none), e.g.:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps API failed\")\n#                ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^  only the first positional argument supplied\n```\n\nBecause `error_detail` is missing, Python raises the *TypeError* you see.\n\n---\n\n## Quick checklist to fix it  \n\n| Step | What to do | Why |\n|------|------------|-----|\n| **1\ufe0f\u20e3 Locate the raise** | Open `C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py` and go to line\u202f13 (or a few lines around it). | That\u2019s where the exception is being instantiated. |\n| **2\ufe0f\u20e3 Decide what information you want** | Do you need both a user\u2011friendly message **and** a technical detail (e.g., the original exception, HTTP status, etc.)? | The constructor was designed to capture both. |\n| **3\ufe0f\u20e3 Pass both arguments** | Example: <br>`raise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request failed\", str(e))` <br>or <br>`raise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request failed\", {\"status\": resp.status_code, \"url\": url})` | Satisfies the signature (`error_message`, `error_detail`). |\n| **4\ufe0f\u20e3 (Optional) Make the second argument optional** | If you often only have a message, change the class definition to give `error_detail` a default value: <br>```python\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail=None):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n``` | Then you can raise it with just one argument and still keep the extra field for cases where you have more info. |\n| **5\ufe0f\u20e3 Re\u2011run the script** | After fixing the raise (or the class), execute the script again to confirm the error is gone. | Verify the fix works. |\n| **6\ufe0f\u20e3 Add logging (best practice)** | Inside the `except` block, log the full traceback before re\u2011raising: <br>`logger.exception(\"Google Maps API error\")` | Gives you a complete stack trace in logs without losing the original exception. |\n\n---\n\n## Example \u2013 Full corrected snippet  \n\nBelow is a **minimal, self\u2011contained** version of what `GoogleMap.py` might look like, with the fix applied and a small improvement (making `error_detail` optional and adding logging).\n\n```python\n# C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\nimport logging\nimport requests\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    error_message : str\n        Human\u2011readable description of the problem.\n    error_detail : Any, optional\n        Extra technical information (original exception, API payload, etc.).\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail=None):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n\n\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\n    \"\"\"\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and returns (lat, lng).\n\n    Raises\n    ------\n    HolidayAgentException\n        If the request fails or the API returns an error status.\n    \"\"\"\n    url = \"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json\"\n    params = {\"address\": place_name, \"key\": api_key}\n\n    try:\n        response = requests.get(url, params=params, timeout=10)\n        response.raise_for_status()          # raises HTTPError for 4xx/5xx\n        data = response.json()\n\n        if data.get(\"status\") != \"OK\":\n            # API returned a logical error (e.g., ZERO_RESULTS)\n            raise HolidayAgentException(\n                f\"Google Maps API error for '{place_name}'\",\n                {\"status\": data.get(\"status\"), \"error_message\": data.get(\"error_message\")}\n            )\n\n        location = data[\"results\"][0][\"geometry\"][\"location\"]\n        return location[\"lat\"], location[\"lng\"]\n\n    except requests.RequestException as e:\n        # Network\u2011level problem (timeout, DNS, connection reset, etc.)\n        logger.exception(\"Network error while calling Google Maps API\")\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\"Failed to reach Google Maps service\", str(e))\n\n    except (KeyError, IndexError) as e:\n        # Unexpected response shape\n        logger.exception(\"Unexpected response structure from Google Maps\")\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\"Malformed response from Google Maps\", e)\n```\n\n### What changed?\n\n| Change | Reason |\n|--------|--------|\n| `error_detail=None` in `HolidayAgentException.__init__` | Makes the second argument optional, preventing the same TypeError if you later raise the exception with only a message. |\n| Added **docstrings** and type hints | Improves readability and helps IDEs/static analysers. |\n| Wrapped the API call in a `try/except` block that **logs** the full traceback (`logger.exception`) before re\u2011raising the custom exception. | Gives you a clean log entry while still bubbling the error up to the caller. |\n| Used `response.raise_for_status()` and explicit check of `data[\"status\"]` | Distinguishes HTTP errors from logical API errors. |\n| Provided **meaningful error_detail** (dict or string) when raising the exception. | Gives downstream code (or a UI) something useful to display or store. |\n\n---\n\n## How to test the fix quickly  \n\n```python\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    import os\n\n    # Put a valid Google Maps API key in an env var for the test\n    API_KEY = os.getenv(\"GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY\", \"YOUR_FAKE_KEY_FOR_TEST\")\n    try:\n        lat, lng = get_place_coordinates(\"Taj Mahal, India\", API_KEY)\n        print(f\"Coordinates: {lat}, {lng}\")\n    except HolidayAgentException as he:\n        print(\"Custom exception caught:\")\n        print(\"  Message :\", he)\n        print(\"  Detail  :\", he.detail)\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\n```\n\n*If the API key is missing or invalid you\u2019ll see a nicely formatted `HolidayAgentException` with the underlying error detail, instead of the cryptic `TypeError` you got before.*\n\n---\n\n## TL;DR \u2013 One\u2011line fix (if you don\u2019t want to touch the class)\n\nIf you prefer **not** to modify `HolidayAgentException`, just change the raise on line\u202f13 to supply a dummy second argument:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request failed\", None)\n```\n\nor, if you have an underlying exception `e`:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request f