: resp.status_code, "url": url})` | Satisfies the signature (`error_message`, `error_detail`). |\n| **4\ufe0f\u20e3 (Optional) Make the second argument optional** | If you often only have a message, change the class definition to give `error_detail` a default value: <br>```python\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail=None):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n``` | Then you can raise it with just one argument and still keep the extra field for cases where you have more info. |\n| **5\ufe0f\u20e3 Re\u2011run the script** | After fixing the raise (or the class), execute the script again to confirm the error is gone. | Verify the fix works. |\n| **6\ufe0f\u20e3 Add logging (best practice)** | Inside the `except` block, log the full traceback before re\u2011raising: <br>`logger.exception("Google Maps API error")` | Gives you a complete stack trace in logs without losing the original exception. |\n\n---\n\n## Example – Full corrected snippet  \n\nBelow is a **minimal, self\u2011contained** version of what `GoogleMap.py` might look like, with the fix applied and a small improvement (making `error_detail` optional and adding logging).\n\n```python\n# C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\nimport logging\nimport requests\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    """Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    error_message : str\n        Human\u2011readable description of the problem.\n    error_detail : Any, optional\n        Extra technical information (original exception, API payload, etc.).\n    """\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail=None):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n\n\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\n    """\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and 