ps request failed", {"status": resp.status_code, "url": url})` | Satisfies the signature (`error_message`, `error_detail`). |\n| **4\ufe0f\u20e3 (Optional) Make the second argument optional** | If you often only have a message, change the class definition to give `error_detail` a default value: <br>```python\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail=None):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n``` | Then you can raise it with just one argument and still keep the extra field for cases where you have more info. |\n| **5\ufe0f\u20e3 Re\u2011run the script** | After fixing the raise (or the class), execute the script again to confirm the error is gone. | Verify the fix works. |\n| **6\ufe0f\u20e3 Add logging (best practice)** | Inside the `except` block, log the full traceback before re\u2011raising: <br>`logger.exception("Google Maps API error")` | Gives you a complete stack trace in logs without losing the original exception. |\n\n---\n\n## Example – Full corrected snippet  \n\nBelow is a **minimal, self\u2011contained** version of what `GoogleMap.py` might look like, with the fix applied and a small improvement (making `error_detail` optional and adding logging).\n\n```python\n# C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\nimport logging\nimport requests\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    """Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    error_message : str\n        Human\u2011readable description of the problem.\n    error_detail : Any, optional\n        Extra technical information (original exception, API payload, etc.).\n    """\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail=None):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n\n\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\n    """\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and returns (lat, lng).\n\n    Raises\n    ------\n    HolidayAgentException\n        If the request fails or the API returns an error status.\n    """\n    url = "https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json"\n    params = {"address": place_name, "key": api_key}\n\n    try:\n        response = requests.get(url, params=params, timeout=10)\n        response.raise_for_status()          # raises HTTPError for 4xx/5xx\n        data = response.json()\n\n        if data.get("status") != "OK":\n            # API returned a logical error (e.g., ZERO_RESULTS)\n            raise HolidayAgentException(\n                f"Google Maps API error for \'{place_name}\'",\n                {"status": data.get("status"), "error_message": data.get("error_message")}\n            )\n\n        location = data["results"][0]["geometry"]["location"]\n        return location["lat"], location["lng"]\n\n    except requests.RequestException as e:\n        # Network\u2011level problem (timeout, DNS, connection reset, etc.)\n        logger.exception("Network error while calling Google Maps API")\n        raise HolidayAgentException("Failed to reach Google Maps service", str(e))\n\n    except (KeyError, IndexError) as e:\n        # Unexpected response shape\n        logger.exception("Unexpected response structure from Google Maps")\n        raise HolidayAgentException("Malformed response from Google Maps", e)\n```\n\n### What changed?\n\n| Change | Reason |\n|--------|--------|\n| `error_detail=None` in `HolidayAgentException.__init__` | Makes the second argument optional, preventing the same TypeError if you later raise the exception with only a message. |\n| Added **docstrings** and type hints | Improves readability and helps IDEs/static analysers. |\n| Wrapped the API call in a `try/except` block that **logs** the full traceback (`logger.exception`) before re\u2011raising the custom exception. | Gives you a clean log entry while still bubbling the error up to the caller. |\n| Used `response.raise_for_status()` and explicit check of `data["status"]` | Distinguishes HTTP errors from logical API errors. |\n| Provided **meaningful error_detail** (dict or string) when raising the exception. | Gives downstream code (or a UI) something useful to display or store. |\n\n---\n\n## How to test the fix quickly  \n\n```python\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    import os\n\n    # Put a valid Google Maps API key in an env var for the test\n    API_KEY = os.getenv("GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY", "YOUR_FAKE_KEY_FOR_TEST")\n    try:\n        lat, lng = get_place_coordinates("Taj Mahal, India", API_KEY)\n        print(f"Coordinates: {lat}, {lng}")\n    except HolidayAgentException as he:\n        print("Custom exception caught:")\n        print("  Message :", he)\n        print("  Detail  :", he.detail)\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\n```\n\n*If the API key is missing or invalid you’ll see a nicely formatted `HolidayAgentException` with the underlying error detail, instead of the cryptic `TypeError` you got before.*\n\n---\n\n## TL;DR – One\u2011line fix (if you don’t want to touch the class)\n\nIf you prefer **not** to modify `HolidayAgentException`, just change the raise on line\u202f13 to supply a dummy second argument:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException("Google Maps request failed", None)\n```\n\nor, if you have an underlying exception `e`:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException("Google Maps request failed", str(e))\n```\n\n---\n\n### Next steps for you\n\n1. **Open `GoogleMap.py`** \u2192 locate line\u202f13.  \n2. Apply one of the two fixes above (add the missing argument **or** make the argument optional).  \n3. Run the script again; the `HolidayAgentException` should now be raised correctly, and you’ll get a clear error message instead of a `TypeError`.  \n\nIf you hit any other traceback after this change, paste the new error message here and we can troubleshoot the next layer. Happy coding!', type='TextMessage'), inner_messages=[]), 'name': 'Travel_Planner'}
